Just to add that when I run the tests from the command line I get this error for each test:

Shell: error: Unable to read Dart source 'package:test\src\runner\plugin\remote_platform_helpers.dart'.

Just noticed that the same issue was previously raised but is is closed now
https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/issues/1646
I have rolled back Flutter plugin back to 20.0.3 but getting the same exception and the tests do not run either .....

Deleted all .packages and pubspec.lock files & rerun lutter packages get 

Testing started at 23:35 ...
D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter\bin\cache\dart-sdk\bin\dart.exe --enable-vm-service:60367 D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter\bin\cache\dart-sdk\bin\snapshots\pub.dart.snapshot run test -r json D:/repo__at/_moneyvore/lib_utils/test/util/date_utils_test.dart
Observatory listening on http://127.0.0.1:60367/

**D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter\bin\packages\flutter_test\pubspec.yaml has changed since the pubspec.lock file was generated, please run "pub get" again.**

Process finished with exit code 65

**D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter**  is the directory where I cloned flutter repository.
Needless to say that there is no **packages\flutter_test\pubspec.yaml**  subdirectory under the bin directory .... not sure what is going on.
This should be addressed with the (just published) latest version of the plugin.

Unfortunately the exception is still there with a slightly different stack though.

Is there anything I should check? I think that there are some 'external' factors involved here. I have the same IDE/plugins installed at work and have no issues.

Can you verify that the flutter sdk path in your settings points to a Flutter sdk? Also, if you can include the contents of the `version` file from your sdk, that would be great.

From the stack trace, the issue looks like we must be locating the `<flutter-sdk>/version` file, but the contents don't parse into a valid semver like version.

These are my settings

Flutter SDK directory "D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter"
Is on the path "PATH=.....\nodejs\;D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter\bin;C:\Program....."
Ii have also this environment variable "FLUTTER_ROOT=D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter\bin" (set up in desperation :-) )
Dart version 2.0.0-dev.16.0

But "D:\repo__dart_flutter\__flutter\version" content says **unknown**.

Is that the value you have in the Settings dialog, in `Languages & Frameworks > Flutter`? > But "D:\repo__dart_flutter__flutter\version" content says unknown. So, that file doesn't exist? What do you see if you run `flutter --version`?

Sorry I have not explained that well. 

The version file D:\repo__dart_flutter__flutter\version" exists but it contains a single line with the 'unknown' string.

The Settings in Languages & Frameworks > Flutter dialog returns:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7585117/35473868-f2a208fc-037d-11e8-9dd8-3e66392fe7cf.png)

Ah! Thanks for digging into this.

/cc @tvolkert and @Hixie; it looks like in some cases flutter_tools will write `unknown` into the `version` file.

It should write `0.0.0-unknown` now. It may have been doing that due to an only git version, in which case it should now give the right answer also. It might also give unknown if you used `--depth` to fetch the repo.
This should be addressed with the latest release.
